                        {
                            "defaultConfiguration": {
                                "level": "error"
                            },
                            "fullDescription": {
                                "text": "Angular is a development platform for building mobile and desktop web applications using TypeScript/JavaScript and other languages. Prior to versions 19.2.16, 20.3.14, and 21.0.1, there is a XSRF token leakage via protocol-relative URLs in angular HTTP clients. The vulnerability is a Credential Leak by App Logic that leads to the unauthorized disclosure of the Cross-Site Request Forgery (XSRF) token to an attacker-controlled domain. Angular's HttpClient has a built-in XSRF protection mechanism that works by checking if a request URL starts with a protocol (http:// or https://) to determine if it is cross-origin. If the URL starts with protocol-relative URL (//), it is incorrectly treated as a same-origin request, and the XSRF token is automatically added to the X-XSRF-TOKEN header. This issue has been patched in versions 19.2.16, 20.3.14, and 21.0.1. A workaround for this issue involves avoiding using protocol-relative URLs (URLs starting with //) in HttpClient requests. All backend communication URLs should be hardcoded as relative paths (starting with a single /) or fully qualified, trusted absolute URLs."
                            },
                            "help": {
                                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-66035**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|@angular/common|21.0.1, 20.3.14, 19.2.16|[CVE-2025-66035](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-66035)|\n\nAngular is a development platform for building mobile and desktop web applications using TypeScript/JavaScript and other languages. Prior to versions 19.2.16, 20.3.14, and 21.0.1, there is a XSRF token leakage via protocol-relative URLs in angular HTTP clients. The vulnerability is a Credential Leak by App Logic that leads to the unauthorized disclosure of the Cross-Site Request Forgery (XSRF) token to an attacker-controlled domain. Angular's HttpClient has a built-in XSRF protection mechanism that works by checking if a request URL starts with a protocol (http:// or https://) to determine if it is cross-origin. If the URL starts with protocol-relative URL (//), it is incorrectly treated as a same-origin request, and the XSRF token is automatically added to the X-XSRF-TOKEN header. This issue has been patched in versions 19.2.16, 20.3.14, and 21.0.1. A workaround for this issue involves avoiding using protocol-relative URLs (URLs starting with //) in HttpClient requests. All backend communication URLs should be hardcoded as relative paths (starting with a single /) or fully qualified, trusted absolute URLs.",
                                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-66035\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: @angular/common\nFixed Version: 21.0.1, 20.3.14, 19.2.16\nLink: [CVE-2025-66035](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-66035)\nAngular is a development platform for building mobile and desktop web applications using TypeScript/JavaScript and other languages. Prior to versions 19.2.16, 20.3.14, and 21.0.1, there is a XSRF token leakage via protocol-relative URLs in angular HTTP clients. The vulnerability is a Credential Leak by App Logic that leads to the unauthorized disclosure of the Cross-Site Request Forgery (XSRF) token to an attacker-controlled domain. Angular's HttpClient has a built-in XSRF protection mechanism that works by checking if a request URL starts with a protocol (http:// or https://) to determine if it is cross-origin. If the URL starts with protocol-relative URL (//), it is incorrectly treated as a same-origin request, and the XSRF token is automatically added to the X-XSRF-TOKEN header. This issue has been patched in versions 19.2.16, 20.3.14, and 21.0.1. A workaround for this issue involves avoiding using protocol-relative URLs (URLs starting with //) in HttpClient requests. All backend communication URLs should be hardcoded as relative paths (starting with a single /) or fully qualified, trusted absolute URLs."
                            },
                            "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-66035",
                            "id": "CVE-2025-66035",
                            "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
                            "properties": {
                                "cvssv40_baseScore": 7.7,
                                "cvssv40_vector": "CVSS:4.0/AV:N/AC:L/AT:N/PR:N/UI:N/VC:N/VI:N/VA:N/SC:H/SI:N/SA:N",
                                "precision": "very-high",
                                "security-severity": "8.0",
                                "tags": [
                                    "vulnerability",
                                    "security",
                                    "HIGH"
                                ]
                            },
                            "shortDescription": {
                                "text": "angular: Angular HTTP Client Has XSRF Token Leakage via Protocol-Relative URLs"
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "defaultConfiguration": {
                                "level": "error"
                            },
                            "fullDescription": {
                                "text": "Angular is a development platform for building mobile and desktop web applications using TypeScript/JavaScript and other languages. Prior to 21.0.2, 20.3.15, and 19.2.17, A Stored Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability has been identified in the Angular Template Compiler. It occurs because the compiler's internal security schema is incomplete, allowing attackers to bypass Angular's built-in security sanitization. Specifically, the schema fails to classify certain URL-holding attributes (e.g., those that could contain javascript: URLs) as requiring strict URL security, enabling the injection of malicious scripts. This vulnerability is fixed in 21.0.2, 20.3.15, and 19.2.17."
                            },
                            "help": {
                                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-66412**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|@angular/compiler|21.0.2, 20.3.15, 19.2.17|[CVE-2025-66412](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-66412)|\n\nAngular is a development platform for building mobile and desktop web applications using TypeScript/JavaScript and other languages. Prior to 21.0.2, 20.3.15, and 19.2.17, A Stored Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability has been identified in the Angular Template Compiler. It occurs because the compiler's internal security schema is incomplete, allowing attackers to bypass Angular's built-in security sanitization. Specifically, the schema fails to classify certain URL-holding attributes (e.g., those that could contain javascript: URLs) as requiring strict URL security, enabling the injection of malicious scripts. This vulnerability is fixed in 21.0.2, 20.3.15, and 19.2.17.",
                                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-66412\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: @angular/compiler\nFixed Version: 21.0.2, 20.3.15, 19.2.17\nLink: [CVE-2025-66412](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-66412)\nAngular is a development platform for building mobile and desktop web applications using TypeScript/JavaScript and other languages. Prior to 21.0.2, 20.3.15, and 19.2.17, A Stored Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability has been identified in the Angular Template Compiler. It occurs because the compiler's internal security schema is incomplete, allowing attackers to bypass Angular's built-in security sanitization. Specifically, the schema fails to classify certain URL-holding attributes (e.g., those that could contain javascript: URLs) as requiring strict URL security, enabling the injection of malicious scripts. This vulnerability is fixed in 21.0.2, 20.3.15, and 19.2.17."
                            },
                            "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-66412",
