                        {
                            "defaultConfiguration": {
                                "level": "error"
                            },
                            "fullDescription": {
                                "text": "parse-duraton is software that allows users to convert a human readable duration to milliseconds. Versions prior to 2.1.3 are vulnerable to an event loop delay due to the CPU-bound operation of resolving the provided string, from a 0.5ms and up to ~50ms per one operation, with a varying size from 0.01 MB and up to 4.3 MB respectively, and an out of memory that would crash a running Node.js application due to a string size of roughly 10 MB that utilizes unicode characters. Version 2.1.3 contains a patch."
                            },
                            "help": {
                                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2025-25283**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|parse-duration|2.1.3|[CVE-2025-25283](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-25283)|\n\nparse-duraton is software that allows users to convert a human readable duration to milliseconds. Versions prior to 2.1.3 are vulnerable to an event loop delay due to the CPU-bound operation of resolving the provided string, from a 0.5ms and up to ~50ms per one operation, with a varying size from 0.01 MB and up to 4.3 MB respectively, and an out of memory that would crash a running Node.js application due to a string size of roughly 10 MB that utilizes unicode characters. Version 2.1.3 contains a patch.",
                                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2025-25283\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: parse-duration\nFixed Version: 2.1.3\nLink: [CVE-2025-25283](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2025-25283)\nparse-duraton is software that allows users to convert a human readable duration to milliseconds. Versions prior to 2.1.3 are vulnerable to an event loop delay due to the CPU-bound operation of resolving the provided string, from a 0.5ms and up to ~50ms per one operation, with a varying size from 0.01 MB and up to 4.3 MB respectively, and an out of memory that would crash a running Node.js application due to a string size of roughly 10 MB that utilizes unicode characters. Version 2.1.3 contains a patch."
                            },
