                        {
                            "defaultConfiguration": {
                                "level": "error"
                            },
                            "fullDescription": {
                                "text": "xmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) `DOMParser` and `XMLSerializer` module. xmldom parses XML that is not well-formed because it contains multiple top level elements, and adds all root nodes to the `childNodes` collection of the `Document`, without reporting any error or throwing. This breaks the assumption that there is only a single root node in the tree, which led to issuance of CVE-2022-39299 as it is a potential issue for dependents. Update to @xmldom/xmldom@~0.7.7, @xmldom/xmldom@~0.8.4 (dist-tag latest) or @xmldom/xmldom@>=0.9.0-beta.4 (dist-tag next). As a workaround, please one of the following approaches depending on your use case: instead of searching for elements in the whole DOM, only search in the `documentElement`or reject a document with a document that has more then 1 `childNode`."
                            },
                            "help": {
                                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2022-39353**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|CRITICAL|xmldom||[CVE-2022-39353](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2022-39353)|\n\nxmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) `DOMParser` and `XMLSerializer` module. xmldom parses XML that is not well-formed because it contains multiple top level elements, and adds all root nodes to the `childNodes` collection of the `Document`, without reporting any error or throwing. This breaks the assumption that there is only a single root node in the tree, which led to issuance of CVE-2022-39299 as it is a potential issue for dependents. Update to @xmldom/xmldom@~0.7.7, @xmldom/xmldom@~0.8.4 (dist-tag latest) or @xmldom/xmldom@>=0.9.0-beta.4 (dist-tag next). As a workaround, please one of the following approaches depending on your use case: instead of searching for elements in the whole DOM, only search in the `documentElement`or reject a document with a document that has more then 1 `childNode`.",
                                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2022-39353\nSeverity: CRITICAL\nPackage: xmldom\nFixed Version: \nLink: [CVE-2022-39353](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2022-39353)\nxmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) `DOMParser` and `XMLSerializer` module. xmldom parses XML that is not well-formed because it contains multiple top level elements, and adds all root nodes to the `childNodes` collection of the `Document`, without reporting any error or throwing. This breaks the assumption that there is only a single root node in the tree, which led to issuance of CVE-2022-39299 as it is a potential issue for dependents. Update to @xmldom/xmldom@~0.7.7, @xmldom/xmldom@~0.8.4 (dist-tag latest) or @xmldom/xmldom@>=0.9.0-beta.4 (dist-tag next). As a workaround, please one of the following approaches depending on your use case: instead of searching for elements in the whole DOM, only search in the `documentElement`or reject a document with a document that has more then 1 `childNode`."
                            },
                            "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2022-39353",
                            "id": "CVE-2022-39353",
                            "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
                            "properties": {
                                "cvssv3_baseScore": 9.8,
                                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H",
                                "precision": "very-high",
                                "security-severity": "9.8",
                                "tags": [
                                    "vulnerability",
                                    "security",
                                    "CRITICAL"
                                ]
                            },
                            "shortDescription": {
                                "text": "xmldom: Allows multiple root elements in a DOM tree"
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "defaultConfiguration": {
                                "level": "error"
                            },
                            "fullDescription": {
                                "text": "xmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) `DOMParser` and `XMLSerializer` module. In xmldom versions 0.6.0 and prior and @xmldom/xmldom prior to versions 0.8.12 and 0.9.9, xmldom/xmldom allows attacker-controlled strings containing the CDATA terminator ]]> to be inserted into a CDATASection node. During serialization, XMLSerializer emitted the CDATA content verbatim without rejecting or safely splitting the terminator. As a result, data intended to remain text-only became active XML markup in the serialized output, enabling XML structure injection and downstream business-logic manipulation. This issue has been patched in xmldom version 0.6.0 and @xmldom/xmldom versions 0.8.12 and 0.9.9."
                            },
                            "help": {
                                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2026-34601**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|HIGH|xmldom||[CVE-2026-34601](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-34601)|\n\nxmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) `DOMParser` and `XMLSerializer` module. In xmldom versions 0.6.0 and prior and @xmldom/xmldom prior to versions 0.8.12 and 0.9.9, xmldom/xmldom allows attacker-controlled strings containing the CDATA terminator ]]> to be inserted into a CDATASection node. During serialization, XMLSerializer emitted the CDATA content verbatim without rejecting or safely splitting the terminator. As a result, data intended to remain text-only became active XML markup in the serialized output, enabling XML structure injection and downstream business-logic manipulation. This issue has been patched in xmldom version 0.6.0 and @xmldom/xmldom versions 0.8.12 and 0.9.9.",
                                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2026-34601\nSeverity: HIGH\nPackage: xmldom\nFixed Version: \nLink: [CVE-2026-34601](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-34601)\nxmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) `DOMParser` and `XMLSerializer` module. In xmldom versions 0.6.0 and prior and @xmldom/xmldom prior to versions 0.8.12 and 0.9.9, xmldom/xmldom allows attacker-controlled strings containing the CDATA terminator ]]> to be inserted into a CDATASection node. During serialization, XMLSerializer emitted the CDATA content verbatim without rejecting or safely splitting the terminator. As a result, data intended to remain text-only became active XML markup in the serialized output, enabling XML structure injection and downstream business-logic manipulation. This issue has been patched in xmldom version 0.6.0 and @xmldom/xmldom versions 0.8.12 and 0.9.9."
                            },
                            "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2026-34601",
                            "id": "CVE-2026-34601",
                            "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
                            "properties": {
                                "cvssv3_baseScore": 7.5,
                                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:N/I:H/A:N",
                                "precision": "very-high",
                                "security-severity": "7.5",
                                "tags": [
                                    "vulnerability",
                                    "security",
                                    "HIGH"
                                ]
                            },
                            "shortDescription": {
                                "text": "xmldom: xmldom: XML structure injection via CDATA terminator"
                            }
                        },
                        {
                            "defaultConfiguration": {
                                "level": "warning"
                            },
                            "fullDescription": {
                                "text": "xmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) DOMParser and XMLSerializer module. xmldom versions 0.4.0 and older do not correctly preserve system identifiers, FPIs or namespaces when repeatedly parsing and serializing maliciously crafted documents. This may lead to unexpected syntactic changes during XML processing in some downstream applications. This is fixed in version 0.5.0. As a workaround downstream applications can validate the input and reject the maliciously crafted documents."
                            },
                            "help": {
                                "markdown": "**Vulnerability CVE-2021-21366**\n| Severity | Package | Fixed Version | Link |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|MEDIUM|xmldom|0.5.0|[CVE-2021-21366](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2021-21366)|\n\nxmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) DOMParser and XMLSerializer module. xmldom versions 0.4.0 and older do not correctly preserve system identifiers, FPIs or namespaces when repeatedly parsing and serializing maliciously crafted documents. This may lead to unexpected syntactic changes during XML processing in some downstream applications. This is fixed in version 0.5.0. As a workaround downstream applications can validate the input and reject the maliciously crafted documents.",
                                "text": "Vulnerability CVE-2021-21366\nSeverity: MEDIUM\nPackage: xmldom\nFixed Version: 0.5.0\nLink: [CVE-2021-21366](https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2021-21366)\nxmldom is a pure JavaScript W3C standard-based (XML DOM Level 2 Core) DOMParser and XMLSerializer module. xmldom versions 0.4.0 and older do not correctly preserve system identifiers, FPIs or namespaces when repeatedly parsing and serializing maliciously crafted documents. This may lead to unexpected syntactic changes during XML processing in some downstream applications. This is fixed in version 0.5.0. As a workaround downstream applications can validate the input and reject the maliciously crafted documents."
                            },
                            "helpUri": "https://avd.aquasec.com/nvd/cve-2021-21366",
                            "id": "CVE-2021-21366",
                            "name": "LanguageSpecificPackageVulnerability",
                            "properties": {
                                "cvssv3_baseScore": 4.3,
                                "cvssv3_vector": "CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:R/S:U/C:N/I:L/A:N",
                                "precision": "very-high",
                                "security-severity": "4.3",
